                        "content": "A client diagnosed with anxiety is starting therapy with lorazepam. Which factor in the client's history would prompt the nurse to consult with the primary health care provider before administering the medication?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nLorazepam is a benzodiazepine and is contraindicated in hypersensitivity, cross-sensitivity with other benzodiazepines, comatose state, preexisting central nervous system depression, uncontrolled severe pain, and narrow-angle glaucoma because benzodiazepines can further increase the intraocular pressure. It also is contraindicated in pregnancy and in clients who are breast-feeding/chest-feeding. None of the other options are relevant to the administration of lorazepam.\n\nClient Needs: Safe and Effective Care Environment\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Take Action\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Psychiatric: Barbiturate and Sedative-Hypnotics\nHealth Problem: Mental Health: Anxiety Disorder\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Implementation\nPriority Concepts: Collaboration, Safety\nStrategies: Subject\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, contraindications to lorazepam use. Remember that this medication is a benzodiazepine and is contraindicated in narrow-angle glaucoma. This will assist you in answering questions similar to this one.",
                        "id": "0a80ed4cefba4c0cb827d0d3eca57b0f",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
