                        "content": "The nurse is working with a client who shows signs of benzodiazepine withdrawal. The nurse would suspect that the client has suddenly discontinued taking which prescribed medication?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nThe only benzodiazepine presented in the options is diazepam. Benzodiazepines are effective only when used for short-term therapy. Short-acting benzodiazepines can produce withdrawal symptoms within 1 to 2 days, whereas long-acting benzodiazepines take 5 to 10 days for withdrawal symptoms to occur following discontinuation. Manifestations include insomnia, agitation, anxiety, irritability, nausea, and diaphoresis. The other options list an antipsychotic (haloperidol) and antidepressants (fluoxetine and sertraline).\n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Analyze Cues\nCognitive Ability: Analyzing\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Psychiatric: Barbiturate and Sedative-Hypnotics\nHealth Problem: Mental Health: Addictions\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Assessment\nPriority Concepts: Clinical Judgment, Safety\nStrategies: Subject\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, benzodiazepine withdrawal, and recall the classifications of the medications in the options. Sertraline, haloperidol, and fluoxetine are incorrect because they do not identify a benzodiazepine. Remember that diazepam is a benzodiazepine.\n ",
                        "id": "9c8edd54404c4f6e80e68fdb6c74624b",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
